16/12/2005
ISTANBUL, Turkey -- The landmark trial of a writer accused of offending Turkish national identity was suspended soon after it began on Friday (16 December). An Istanbul judge said the prosecution could not proceed until the justice ministry had approved it. Novelist Orhan Pamuk is accused of telling a Swiss newspaper that 30,000 Kurds and one million Armenians have died in Turkey over the past century. The next hearing is scheduled for 7 February. 
In other news, Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan met with new US Ambassador to Turkey Ross Wilson on Thursday. This was their first formal meeting. (BBC, LA Times, Bloomberg - 16/12/05; NTV, BBC, TurkishPress - 15/12/05) 
